For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without using the means of force.
They spend ten billion dollars a year supporting language schools and building universities abroad, pushing their entertainment industry to foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
But Beijing is not doing well.
The state media there is talking about the plan to turn tourism into a driving force for economic change and modernisation.
Last year, however, the number of arrivals rose by only 3.8%, and roughly 80% of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, judging the situation in the world's most populous country, the professor of economics from the Beijing University Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for everything is China's visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China; the citizens of the other countries have to get their visa in advance.
Therefore, at the Chinese authorities in the US, the crowds are comparable to the Chinese New Year's celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you don't want to wait long hours in line for it, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic obstacles.
The Journal of Economics and Finance study showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China's gross domestic product and lives there less than one percent of the population, visited 1.8 million Americans.
China often deepens this problem itself when it uses tourism to realise its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted transportation to South Korea in the spring as part of the rupture around the South Korean missile system, the South Koreans repaid it and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year on year, while Japan grew by 85 percent.
All of this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US Central Bank, the Fed may have left China as much as $190 billion due to China's foreign trips, while China will receive about $35 billion per year in its currency sale to incoming tourists.
According to official figures on balance of payments developments, last year China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism, equivalent to 44% of the total Chinese surplus in the goods trade.
A small number of tourists, therefore, who are anxious to prevent a capital outflow, are causing a very painful blow.
However, the above mentioned factors are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many places in China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, fewer than a million foreigners lived throughout China.
There are several cities in the United States.
Even Japan, which is not exactly the crossroads of immigration, has twice as much.
A number of scientific works show that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
In China, however, you will virtually not find them.
It will be politically difficult to solve these problems, but the step that is being taken is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian states, in particular India and Vietnam, have been making a great effort recently to simplify and lower visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
