Since 2005, a group of activists have regularly returned to the Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct the fateful night of 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by Kuklux Klan members.
No one has ever been tried for murder before.
"It is a wonder that in all these years no single person has been arrested - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity," Tyrone Brooks, who helps to organize the reconstruction of the event, has been heard.
"It's a stain on our history and the burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former congressman of the state of Georgia and a lifelong civil rights fighter.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event presents a dramatic call for action. Every year, the Monroe community is reminded that justice has not been done.
"We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," said Brooks.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot be initiated."
The medical examiner covers one of the bodies of the lynching victims at Moore's Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to the FBI files that received NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and the surrounding counties were scheduled to participate in lynching.
But no one has ever been prosecuted before.
Despite the fact that suspects have remained at large for decades, civil rights supporters claim that both the reasons for lynching - politics and sex - were known to all citizens of the city.
In April 1946, on the basis of the decision of the Supreme Court, the inhabitants of Georgia, for the first time ever, gained the right to take part in the elections scheduled for the summer.
And just during the summer election, according to the FBI, a black-skinned farmer Roger Malcom was supposed to stab the owner of Barnett Hester's white-land claim to be his wife.
In the city, Brooks said that Hester was loitering with Malcom's wife Dorothy and bringing her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, the prominent owner of the white-skin property, Loy Harrison, posted $600 for Malcom.
Dorothy and cousin Mae Murray and George Dorsey accompanied him to the prison.
On their return from the prison, just before the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects made their way through.
"As it turns out, the murders were planned and organized by Harrison," led by the FBI.
"It is also clear that there has been a secret agreement between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in lynching, but also got rid of the evidence and hid the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks made his point more briefly.
"It was a massacre for election law," he said.
"The murders had a clear subtext for all black people:" This is how you end up if you sign up and vote. "
The annual reconstruction of the event at Moore's Ford Bridge has been organized for almost ten years by Cassandra Greene.
Her performance is figurative, captivating and concise, showing deep-rooted racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
