Latest results of tests for setting the age limit for asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of asylum seekers' tests in Sweden, which have been subjected to a new method assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people have been questioned as over 18 years of age, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (Rèttsmedicinalverket) began to carry out new tests at the beginning of this year.
The aim of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants in the framework of the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migration Sverket) was criticised for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted a total of 2481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017 to investigate 6880 cases and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results.
80% (2002) were assessed as over 18 years of age, while in the next 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency considered that the respondent was "possibly older than 18 years of age."
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the respondent was "possibly under the age of 18."
Tests shall only be carried out if the age of the respondent is questionable.
According to Johan GÃ ¶ ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month, the statistics stick to the old tracks and the numbers are very similar," he said for The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated for over 18 years does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and stated that in 442 cases it was found that "the person questioned was 18 years old or older."
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent said he would be 18 years old this year.
A medical method of determining age was also found to be critical, which includes X-ray of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are subsequently assessed by dentists and X-rays.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who is involved, among other things, in assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age when the person underwent puberty.
"I had reason to think about this issue and I do not think that these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we cannot determine age with precision, we should not pretend otherwise, "said Metro for the newspaper.
The forensic medical agency Agency's GÃ'ransson advocated the decision: "Generally speaking, the risk of misassessment of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the person questioned is just below the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10% of all questions. '
