How the financial rules of football affect the transfer of Neymar to Paris
The rules limiting the financing of European football clubs will not in any way interfere with Neymar's record transfer from Barcelona to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The financial fair play (FFP) rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 provide that the PSG will have to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona has paid EUR 222 million only to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will claim a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
There are several financial conditions for Neymar's transfer to France.
Since the PSG team is funded by a rich Qatar family that has become rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already star football family.
Clubs can spend huge amounts to buy players, but, on the other hand, they have to prove legitimate sources of income, allowing them to cover the overhead costs of football-related business activities.
The FFP introduced Michel Platini after being placed as Director of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that were owed in pursuit of new reinforcements would ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to provide them.
In 2011, FFP's rules redirected its attention from club debt to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spend a hefty sum on players to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
In the current three-year test period ending in 2018, clubs may report losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Cheferin is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
"The FFP rules still apply and we are committed to strengthening them in the future," said Andrea Traverso, the Associated Press last week, who oversees compliance with the FFP rules.
Although the PSG paid the amount for the redemption of Neymar in a one-off payment, it may spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract for accounting purposes.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so that the transfer can be broken down into EUR 44,4 million each year for five years.
The first wave of FFP's highest sanctions hit the PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, owned by Abu Dhabi.
The PSG fined EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and the order to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is careful about teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatar company is sponsoring the PSG once the funding exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
In 2014, UEFA decided that the amount of funds provided by Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
According to some reports, part of Neymar's income in the PSG could be paid by the MS Organizing Commission in football 2022 in Qatar.
However, the PSG and the leaders of MS 2022 in Qatar denied the fat that Neymat should become the ambassador to MS in football and that such maneuver would easily reveal UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to Tuesday's insider statement, UEFA has not initiated any investigation into Neymar's transfer to the PSG.
The source of this report wished to remain anonymous as it was not entitled to comment on the PSG situation, the Associated Press stated.
The latest published accounts show that PSG closed the year 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542,4 million.
The accounts for the current financial year have not yet been published.
The PSG expects Neymar's arrival to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchanting and selling jerseys.
The club promises to increase its turnover by up to 30 percent from signing the contract.
The leaders of the Spanish League, clearly concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar's departure, arguing that the PSG would violate FFP rules.
"This is a clear case of" financial doping 'of the club and of the state, "said the president of la League Javier Teba for the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the ownership of the PSG by the Qatar syndicate.
Arsenal's manager Arsenal Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports mogul, shares La League's position on the club's financing.
"It is the result of ownership that has changed the football world from the ground up in the last 15 years," Wenger let himself be heard on Thursday.
