NHS prescribes controversial HIV medicine to 10,000 patients
Patients have been given access to "transformative 'treatment for HIV prevention since September, following a decision by the Supreme Court on the financing of NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to finance the probationary period after the Court of Appeal supported the decision of the Supreme Court of last year, stating that the NHS had the funds to pay for the PrEP despite the statement that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by NHS England from the mouth of Director General Simon Stevens as a "major intervention ', while National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a" decisive moment'.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will be connected in October and by April 2018 will be fully implemented throughout England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug administered before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that the PrEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV among patients at risk.
Pre-sex application of the PrEP means that there are sufficient specific medicines in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
The patients tested include homosexuals or bisexual men, transsexual people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign the consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also register in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will cost taxpayers £10 million, and the NHS of England signed a contract this week to distribute drugs after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of the PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: "This important intervention should complement and make full use of the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges for human health. '
Deborah Gold, CEO of NAT (National Aids Trust) said, "We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If the PrEP is administered correctly and the patients are threatened, it will offer the possibility of a change in the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients who are at high risk of HIV infection with a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to any need to talk to a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement. '
Ian Green, CEO of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is available to every patient.
We now have the PrEP trial drug and are on the right track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection. '
The shadow health minister Sharon Hodgson said: "The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
The subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of the PriEP.
It is now important that we start tests as soon as possible throughout the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to end the spread of HIV in society together. '
