The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years describes the new document "Whose Streets?" which will be launched into the cinema on August 11.
It's a story about survival and protests, love and resistance, strength and indignation, told from the perspective of people living in the community, who go out on the streets and demand answers.
On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headband - on a topic that had been discussed many times before - "about experience with black people."
"Remember when I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" remembers the conversation.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"There was no way I wouldn't take her with me," said Ferrell later.
"Today's events are the culmination... of the past.
