A few weeks later, Ferrell met a later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan, during the evening demonstration.
Folayan said that he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "document" ongoing events.
But Ferrell thought, "Are you working on a document or trying to find a story that can be used?"
Such a type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often white people, who wanted to make money on pain and determination.
As the Folayan explained in a recent interview: "We have heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that."
Folayan has already established cooperation with co-director Damon Davis, who is a respected local artist who deals with the topic of death row prisoners.
His participation in the project was also inspired by Ferrell, along with six other locals, who were followed by the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's murder.
"In this document no one speaks for us, but it is our testimony," said Davis.
"That was important to me - how these people will be represented - because in the same way I will be represented."
While the aim of the document was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an attempt to show that the movement "is not about the Savior leader, but about the community's rapprochement," said Folayan - it proved that she is the most open to participation in filming.
The document "Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, for example, how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," said Ferrell with a smile on her face at the thought of the first moment when she saw the final version of the document.
"But I understand that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I have to open up."
In addition, Ferrell's story highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in the wider aspect of Black Lives Matter.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created in response to the killing of a teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 on social media campaign under # BlackLivesMatter - call themselves weirdos.
"Black eccentric women in leading positions are ultimately behind the movement," said Ferrell, "because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the burden of these events. "
Folayan agrees with this statement and adds that "the movement is in fact supported by black women and a great many eccentric black women."
However, he insists that "this is not just an aphromatic matter," and Ferrell is not the main hero of the document because of her views.
"It was she who was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"that she was the one who found herself in the front lines is not a coincidence, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black strange woman is dangerous.
