And Becoming Resemblance: Artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and dark - suspended from the ceiling on the wires. Each one of them seems to have fallen out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were made by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorised disclosure of classified wikiLeaks cables.
The new exhibition, launched on August 2nd, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, which combines her experience with technology, informatics and art, and Manning - a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the presidency of the United States.
An algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, produced a Dewey-Hagborg razor-sharp, if not an intellectual comment about DNA compliance - as well as the many ways that DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since she was a young woman. She was sentenced in 2013 by 20 indictments, including violation of six spy laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photos were held by prison employees. Only one black and white photograph of a lower quality was leaked to the public, on which Manning, visibly concerned, is sitting in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, there were still positive responses to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and gum - to create a picture of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were preparing an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait," explained Dewey-Hagborg at the opening of the new exhibition.
But neither visitors nor photography were allowed, so they contacted Chelsea asking if she was interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her trapped muse became friends in two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would have happened if Chelsea had been pardoned and could have participated in the exhibition in person.
Indeed, President Obama applied for Manning's release a few days after the release of the comic book, which was a welcome change after several insufferable years in a military prison in Kansas.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war with people who are seeking to release government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite resentment in areas that he should support with his tweets.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything is happening for a reason."
Under a statement by an artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the last name is dotted with the heart) after the end of "self-fractionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By placing 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to a sophisticated scientific dictionary artist), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least in biological terms, we all are.
"I hope that people will take it away from us, that our genome does not matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg.
"DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning as she emerges in the form of King Kong from United States Disabled Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never let yourself be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," said the Philadelphia artist.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not visited the exhibition personally - which was predicted in a comic book - but when she does, she will be welcomed in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genome images, lined up as a mob of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including an almost 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which its genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"In the past they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to feel the crowd," said Dewey-Hagborg about portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and frees her."
