Startups that help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Erretto wanted to measure the satisfaction of her e-commerce startup employees, but she didn't find the appropriate research.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And even though she promised anonymity to the survey, some employees expressed their mistrust of the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Erretto, the owner of the hair care company Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, who employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New human-resource startups are constantly emerging in the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific purpose of measuring employees' obligations, startups allow companies to make quick votes, target specific teams and demographic groups, further offer the complete anonymity of employees and the hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow informants to bypass their superiors and contact the directors directly.
"There are tools on the market such as Meal and Fitbit, which monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Glint startup based in Reedwood City.
Erretto said that Glint made her more aware of what her employees thought and felt in three years.
In addition to rapid surveys and the voting of specific teams, Glint offers a company thermal map and a brief overview of groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - enabling the user to work on the correction.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is wobbling in scandals after a former employee has published a post on his blog describing the corporate environment and harassing employees who dare speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the "Let's Talk Payments" website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and complexity sector by 2020 can exceed $11.8 billion.
Startup Convercent from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Almost 600 Convergent clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
He recently accepted Uber under his wing as well.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable "flash" surveys, collect confidential information in real time and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behaviour.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, the complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The Court of Public Opinion has authorised regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and executive director of the Convercent startup.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behaviour - and if regulators do not act - it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotting, employee exhaustion or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25 000 people across 500 locations, uses Convercent for more than a year to raise employees' awareness of corporate principles and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate management.
Earlier, if the employee wanted to report any problems, he had to trace the phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, formally lodge a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general manager of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no reliable way of monitoring employees' complaints before.
Now that the company is using Convercent, rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never been reached before by managers sitting in offices, miles away from the real solution to complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment, is ensured.
"It is approaching a holistic, overall view of employees' experience," said Vitrano, who runs Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from litigation by employees."
The companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed after Enron's fall on the abuse of employees' ethical rights, said Quinlan.
But only when "the social media lit up the whole thing," companies began to realize that they could not simply hide their skeletons in the closet in the online world.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by bold capital investors who supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent withdrew $10 million in total from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital and eventually took out $47 million of capital.
Glint received $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and received $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
The growing number of research clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high pay and interesting projects.
Employees want to see that they are accepted and appreciated and that they spend their time on a society that seeks a positive mission.
"If people are happy in their work, they perceive that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, striving for the success of society," said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Benefits of LinkedIn, who uses Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money if companies and companies thrive, if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool emerges in the market to ensure the commitment and commitment of employees to society, it is no wonder that there are many investors who will support this effort.
According to working culture experts, it is important to have data on the satisfaction of employees.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that when a company requests feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if change does not happen quickly - in the worst case scenario at all - it can cause disappointment and lack of interest for employees.
"Once you have asked for 4000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of advice at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies that relied too much on the data itself.
"Because once you don't finish things, the employees start asking themselves," Did they hear me?
Do they care about me?
And if not, why should I care? '""
Madison Reed, which now regularly carries out a survey of employees every month, can solve the problem by one day thanks to Glint, said Erretto.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and communication quality, Erretto was able to reorganise several teams within the company and start training communication to successfully resolve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday receives a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in a field known to be a frequent redundancy in the long term.
"If you do not seek to create a transparent working environment, employees will not trust you," said Vitrano.
"And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt. "
