Graphic novel creation: story about A Castle in England
The small castle of Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video of Squeeze and its refuge was also found by Margaret Thatcher during the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney witnessed 700 years of stormy history from his cosy place near the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, which inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County - a famous predilection for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the handwriting of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me," says Rhodes with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter, I feel a personal connection."
The Graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who have lived in the castle of Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Eduardo period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It is not, however, the first book of Rhodes inspired by archives: it is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of inspired documents from the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by a thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the '70s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days, you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm back in time.
How I love archives! "
For someone who is so fascinated with old papers, there is support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of living almost four months in the castle almost like a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I have extended my stay a little longer.")
Rhodes spent his time studying the Victorian "new" castle, going through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of the hyena on the wall and bottles that have been dumped in a ditch for centuries.
He walked the grounds and examined the ruins of the old castle, spoke to gamekeepers, gardeners, and sometimes also to artists who worked on illustrations of his book.
He was drinking whiskey and writing at night.
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as National Trust gained access to documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff only began to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words like "aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands at the attic."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing the property: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I did come across one case where two families were struggling over the birch.
Stop it, people! "
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a stepping stone and dig deeper into English history, including the story called The Labourer, who follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising in 1381.
"I found a record of a revolt in 1380 castle called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," said Rhodes.
"The English uprising actually began in this area and I thought that mutiny was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected after all. "
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of the Jesuit priest, who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was unveiled).
Rhodes' favorite family is Darrell: "I was intrigued by the male race - then men were always in debt and spent money on things they could not afford.
The different generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old women - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to confuse the heads of the heiress. "
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is searching for other adventures.
Recently he returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he sucked inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was consumed by nature.
It's a strange place for Scotney, though.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I thought," Now I'm going to get the hell back into real life. "
