Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, the new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million U.S. residents and 300,000 patients in the UK is causing abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and milk products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at Washington University have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to produce immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna's study director explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the degradation of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales are tilted to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of the research, scientists found the presence of immune cells supporting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We found a connection between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells. "
At the same time, he suggested that if the same thing proved to apply to humans, the combination of L. reuteri and tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
The postgraduate researcher, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in the course of the study of certain types of immune cells supporting body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of same mice kept separate cells.
It derived from the fact that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbioma - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mouse intestine was tested using the DNA grading method, and researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells missing from the second group of mice.
Mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked intestinal microbioma - so they did not develop this type of immune cells - was given L. reuteri bacteria - and formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers have grown L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that have been stored in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turns out to be a by-product of tryptophane metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that people have the same tolerant cells as mice and most of us keep L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably seek to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population. '
