The White House Props cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the US manufacturing industry that took place last month came to $24,000 according to the Navy records issued by TIME weekly.
The Green White Helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the top of the program of July 17 in the White House, which was a show of American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials were looking at a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was built next to the Maine yacht, the Wisconsin fire truck, and the Mississippi forklift.
A White House military officer issued a fragmental order, or FRAGO, and applied for the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the landing of a helicopter on South Lawn in an "emergency" event, reported Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for managing the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such an important event," wrote HMX-1 in an e-mail to your superior, Deputy Navy Commander for Aviation the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7: 00 p.m. for the show, which is scheduled to start at 3: 00 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire place was cleared out, which was planned between 6: 00 and 9: 00 p.m.
The e-mail also stated that if there is a delay in departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for return flight due to a working time regulation.
The original crew stayed on the scene that evening, along with the helicopter, along with a unit of security personnel.
From the records - which were obtained by TIME weekly - it was not apparent whether the other crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prevents state officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible breach of this Regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," wrote the commander.
"Sounds like you've been blocked," said the deputy commander.
This "Made in America" parade was marked by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the President advocated health reform, which passed through the Senate and talked about trying to keep the government regulations in check.
The use of means of air transport such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was riding in the background during his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
"The White House is pleased with the" Made in America 'show presented by products from all 50 states produced by Americans from American materials, "said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landing in the Washington and South Lawn area and train possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with the utmost precision.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current crew training, stated by the state official.
The helicopter unit flew another 11 hours in the "non-presidential support missions" on the same day.
The White House stated that no further props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky stated that the company was in no way involved in the negotiations on the issue of a helicopter on South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and the exact costs of the show are difficult to identify, according to the Navy.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, the reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24 380 per flight hour.
Unit records indicate 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"Putting taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenditure is very misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs. '
According to the 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement of DoD expenditure does not include personnel costs but includes fuel costs, maintenance costs and contractual costs.
Then White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for show purposes.
"The idea of the show that is taking place this week is to present the products produced in the USA," said Spicer.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defence of our state and that they provide work to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and the other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact is to be recalled. "
It's not clear if Trump was looking at a helicopter while he was on his rounds at South Lawn, but he certainly only sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House Trump approached a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president, "I own three."
